The Threat Fits in Your Pocket
Why Disconnecting Internet-Facing PLCs Is Necessary — and Not Enough



Joshua Brunner
Class A Water Treatment Operator  |  OT Security Researcher
OT-Quest  |  June 2026




Why This Paper Exists
On April 7, 2026, the EPA, FBI, CISA, NSA, Department of Energy, and U.S. Cyber Command jointly confirmed what many in the water sector had feared: Iranian-affiliated threat actors¹ are actively exploiting internet-facing programmable logic controllers at U.S. water, wastewater, and energy facilities. The federal response, appropriately, centers on removing PLCs and HMIs from public internet exposure.
This paper argues that disconnecting internet-facing devices is a necessary first step — but one that leaves a second attack surface entirely unaddressed. The tools required to reach that surface require no special procurement, no technical sophistication, and no questions at a purchase counter. This paper examines the physical access threat vector that remains after the network door is closed, and argues that culture, physical access controls, and operator awareness are not secondary concerns — they are the next frontier.




A Note on Tooling and Methodology
The tools referenced in this paper are intentionally low-cost and openly available. Nation-state actors and sophisticated threat groups have access to custom implants, zero-day exploits, and purpose-built OT attack frameworks that far exceed what is described here. This paper does not address that ceiling.
It addresses the floor — the tools that require no special access, no significant budget, and no questions at a purchase counter. A Raspberry Pi, a USB drive, a thirty-dollar device from an electronics retailer. The choice is deliberate: if a municipal water facility cannot defend against the simplest version of this threat, the sophisticated version is an academic concern. Close the easy doors first.
Readers looking for analysis of advanced persistent threat tooling in ICS environments are directed to resources from Dragos, CISA, and the broader OT security research community. This series exists to translate that body of work into the language and context of the operator — the person who is already in the room.

A Note to Operators: This Is Not an Attack Manual
The threat actors targeting U.S. water infrastructure do not need this paper. CyberAv3ngers and groups like them have purpose-built tooling, dedicated infrastructure, and operational playbooks that go far beyond anything described here. They already have their methods.
This document does not teach an attack. It describes the floor of what is possible so that operators can recognize it — the unfamiliar hardware, the USB drive that should not be there, the contractor behavior that does not feel right. The goal is awareness, not capability.
Recognition is the first defensive layer. You cannot defend against something you have never been told exists.
1. The Advisory Is Right. And It Is Not Enough.
The April 7th joint advisory represents the most significant federal action on water sector OT security in years. Six agencies issuing a coordinated warning is not routine. The targeting of Rockwell Automation Allen-Bradley PLCs — the hardware found in an enormous percentage of U.S. water infrastructure — is not theoretical. Real disruptions have occurred. Facilities have had PLC project files wiped, HMI displays manipulated, and process control configurations altered by actors who were never physically present.
The mechanism is documented and significant: CyberAv3ngers are using Rockwell Automation’s own Studio 5000 Logix Designer software to establish accepted connections to victim PLCs. They are not exploiting a software vulnerability in the traditional sense — they are using the exact tools that legitimate engineers use to program and maintain these controllers. To most detection tooling, the resulting network traffic looks like normal engineering activity. The advisory’s recommendation — remove those devices from public internet exposure — is correct. And it is the right first step precisely because it eliminates that access path entirely.
But here is the question the advisory does not answer:
What does the threat look like after the PLC is no longer internet-facing?
The answer is: it looks like a USB drive in someone's pocket. It looks like a laptop bag a contractor set down next to a panel. It looks like a phone on a charging cable near an HMI workstation. It looks like every other Tuesday.
2. The Hollywood Problem
Before we can talk about the real threat, we have to talk about the imaginary one — because the imaginary one is actively making operators less safe.
Operators picture a cyber threat as something external and visible. A van full of equipment. A sophisticated remote actor with blinking screens and specialized hardware. Something that looks different from the normal flow of the workday. This mental model comes from television, from news coverage, from the framing of every major breach story: the attacker is out there, and we need to keep them out.
This framing is not wrong. But it is incomplete in a way that creates a blind spot.
Operators are trained to recognize physical hazards by what they look like. Confined space entry has a visual checklist. Chemical exposure has a smell and a color. Electrical lockout has a physical lock on a physical panel. We categorize risk by pattern recognition — and we are very good at it. Twenty-three years of operations teaches you to read a panel the way you read a face.
Cyber threats routed through physical access exploit exactly that training. They present as nothing. There is no checklist for a USB drive that looks like every other USB drive on the shelf. There is no smell for a Raspberry Pi Zero tucked behind a panel. The threat does not trigger any of the pattern-recognition systems operators have spent careers building.
