4. The Access Question
Each tool above requires something the remote threat actor behind the April advisory does not have: physical presence. And physical presence is far more common than we account for.
Consider who has unescorted or minimally supervised access to OT environments in a typical municipal water system:
Current operators and maintenance staff
Former employees who may retain knowledge of physical layouts and access habits
Contractors performing equipment maintenance, calibration, or upgrades
Chemical vendors with routine delivery and service access
SCADA integrators and automation vendors performing remote-assist sessions via on-site hardware
Meter readers and field technicians with access to remote sites and pump stations
Inspectors, regulators, and auditors with facility-wide access

This is not a list of suspects. This is a list of the people who keep the water running. The point is not that any of them are threats — it is that the threat model has to include the possibility of compromise at any of these points, whether through malicious intent, social engineering, or simple unawareness.
An Iranian threat actor does not need to breach a network-facing PLC if they can convince a contractor to plug in a device, or if a compromised vendor laptop connects to the local OT network during a legitimate service visit. The remote vector and the physical vector are not separate threat categories. They are different phases of the same attack chain.
5. Why This Is an Operator Problem, Not Just a Security Problem
The water sector is staffed overwhelmingly by operators — people whose training, identity, and professional expertise are built around process knowledge, equipment intuition, and public health responsibility. Cybersecurity has historically been treated as something separate: an IT problem, a management concern, a compliance box to check.
This paper is written to argue against that separation — not because operators should become security analysts, but because the threat described in this paper cannot be detected or prevented by a security analyst who isn't in the room.
An operator who understands that a USB drive can compromise an HMI is an operator who questions why a contractor plugged something in without asking. An operator who knows what a Raspberry Pi looks like is an operator who notices the unfamiliar piece of hardware in the cable tray. An operator who understands that their process knowledge is itself a target is an operator who thinks twice before answering detailed questions from an unfamiliar vendor.
Awareness is not a replacement for technical controls. But in an environment where the "security team" may be one person — or no person — and where physical access to critical systems is daily and routine, the operator is the last line of defense the advisory does not address.
6. What Comes After Disconnection
The federal guidance is correct: disconnect internet-facing PLCs and HMIs. Remove the remote attack surface. Require strong authentication on anything that remains accessible. This is not optional and it is not enough.
After disconnection, the following controls become the critical layer:
6.1  USB Port Control
HMI workstations and engineering workstations should have USB ports disabled by policy or physically blocked except during controlled, documented maintenance windows. This is not a novel recommendation — it is consistently underimplemented in the water sector.
6.2  Physical Access Logging and Escort Policies
Unescorted contractor access to OT environments should be the exception, not the norm. Vendor visits should be logged, time-bounded, and supervised where possible. This is operationally disruptive. It is also the only way to establish a baseline of who touched what and when.
6.3  Operator Training on Physical Threat Indicators
Operators should be able to recognize: unfamiliar hardware attached to panels or workstations; USB devices left connected after a vendor visit; unexplained network traffic from the OT segment; HMI behavior that does not match process state. This is not a technical skillset. It is pattern recognition — and operators are already good at pattern recognition.
6.4  Vendor and Contractor Vetting
Supply chain compromise is a documented vector in OT environments. Vendor laptops that connect to OT networks should be treated as potential threat surfaces. Contract language should require notification before any device is connected to the OT segment, and session logging where technically feasible.
6.5  Offline Backups of PLC Project Files
The April advisory documented attackers wiping PLC project files. An offline, verified backup of every PLC program, HMI configuration, and historian database is the difference between a recoverable incident and a prolonged outage. This backup must be physically secured and tested.
7. A Note on Low-Cost Threats
This is the third paper in the Operator Intelligence Series to address low-cost attack tooling. That is not a coincidence and it is not a limitation of the series' scope.
The water sector is overwhelmingly composed of small and mid-sized utilities with limited budgets, small staffs, and no dedicated security function. The threat actors targeting these facilities include nation-state groups with sophisticated tooling — but the access vectors those groups exploit are not sophisticated. Default passwords. Internet-exposed PLCs. Unmonitored USB ports. Flat networks with no segmentation.
The recurring theme of this series is not that attackers are unsophisticated. It is that they do not need to be — because the environments they are targeting have not closed the doors that twelve-dollar hardware can walk through.
Disconnecting internet-facing PLCs closes one of those doors. This paper is about what is standing at the others.




Conclusion
The April 2026 joint advisory is a landmark document. It confirms active compromise. It names the hardware being targeted. It issues clear guidance. It represents the kind of coordinated federal response the water sector has needed.
And the moment utilities comply — the moment the last internet-facing PLC is removed from public exposure — the threat does not go away. It walks in through the front door with a visitor badge and a USB drive in its pocket.
Physical access is the attack surface that no advisory can close from the outside. It requires operators who understand that the threat is real, that it is small, and that it looks like nothing. It requires the people in the room to be the detection layer.
That is not a burden placed on operators from the outside. It is a recognition of what operators already do — read a room, notice what changed, act on what does not belong. The threat is small. The people who will catch it are already in the room. They just need to know what they are looking for.




